# Course Management & On-Trail Navigation

## 5.1 Maps & GPX Files
Interactive route maps and downloadable GPX files are available via the event webpage. Course variations due to weather, climate, or force-majeure circumstances may necessitate last-minute routing adjustments.

---

## 5.2 Route Signage & Arrows
The courses are fully marked with highly visible physical arrows. You do not need secondary navigation aids or map-reading skills. Examples of our signs are shown in the online safety video.

*Absolute Rule:* **Physical course markers on the trail always take priority over GPX files, watch alerts, or existing trail signs (like National Trail or South West Coast Path markers).** If your watch or phone contradicts an Endurancelife arrow on the trail, always follow the physical arrow.

---

## 5.3 Course Splits & Loops
* **Ultra Marathon Splits:** Ultra runners will complete two laps of the Southern loop around Dale / St Anne’s Head. This is clearly signposted and marshalled. At approximately **16.3 miles**, you will encounter an explicit **"Ultra" split sign** which you must follow to head back around St Anne's Head for your second lap. After completing your second lap at approximately **23.4 miles**, follow the default route markers back to the finish line.
* **Other Distance Splits:** Color-coded split arrows are placed at key junctions where routes diverge. Always stay alert to signs matching your distance category.

---

## 5.4 Aid Stations & Nutrition
Water Stations (H2O) and Checkpoints (CP) are positioned strategically along the course **approximately every 6 miles**. For 10K runners, a single water station is located roughly around the midway mark.

* **Provisions:** Aid stations provide fresh water and standard basic nutrition. All supplied snacks are plant-based and vegan-friendly, typically including: GU Energy gels, Luchos Dillitos Energy Blocks, GU Energy Electrolyte Capsules, jelly sweets, bananas, oranges, biscuits, and salted crisps.
* **Nutrition Directive:** **Aid station provisions are meant to complement your own nutrition strategy, not replace it. You are responsible for carrying enough fuel for your race.**
* **Cup Mandate:** Biodegradable cups are available at the 10K water station (though bringing a reusable vessel is encouraged). For all longer distances (Half, Marathon, Ultra), **no single-use cups are provided.** You must carry your own reusable cup, flask, or hydration bladder to receive liquids.
* **Allergies:** It remains your personal responsibility to check the ingredients of any supplied food items before consumption.

